# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: path-traversal-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] In computer science, **canonicalization** (sometimes **standardization** or **normalization**) is a process for converting data that has more than one possible representation into a "standard", "normal", or canonical form.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] This can be done to compare different representations for equivalence, to count the number of distinct data structures, to improve the efficiency of various algorithms by eliminating repeated calculations, or to make it possible to impose a meaningful sorting order.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Files in file systems may in most cases be accessed through multiple filenames.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] For instance in Unix-like systems, the string "`/./`" can be replaced by "`/`".
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] In the C standard library, the function `realpath()` performs this task.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Other operations performed by this function to canonicalize filenames are the handling of `/..` components referring to parent directories, simplification of sequences of multiple slashes, removal of trailing slashes, and the resolution of symbolic links.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Canonicalization of filenames is important for computer security.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] For example, a web server may have a restriction that only files under the cgi directory `C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cgi-bin` may be executed.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] This rule is enforced by checking that the path starts with `C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cgi-bin\` and only then executing it.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] While the file `C:\inetpub\wwwroot\cgi-bin\..\..\..\Windows\System32\cmd.exe` initially appears to be in the cgi directory, it exploits the `..` path specifier to traverse back up the directory hierarchy in an attempt to execute a file outside of `cgi-bin`.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Permitting `cmd.exe` to execute would be an error caused by a failure to canonicalize the filename to the simplest representation, `C:\Windows\System32\cmd.exe`, and is called a directory traversal vulnerability.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] With the path canonicalized, it is clear the file should not be executed.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] In Unicode, many accented letters can be represented in more than one way.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] For example, *é* can be represented in Unicode as the Unicode character U+0065 (LATIN SMALL LETTER E) followed by the character U+0301 (COMBINING ACUTE ACCENT), but it can also be represented as the precomposed character U+00E9 (LATIN SMALL LETTER E WITH ACUTE).
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] This makes string comparison more complicated, since every possible representation of a string containing such glyphs must be considered.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] To deal with this, Unicode provides the mechanism of canonical equivalence.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] In this context, canonicalization is Unicode normalization.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Variable-width encodings in the Unicode standard, in particular UTF-8, may cause an additional need for canonicalization in some situations.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Namely, by the standard, in UTF-8 there is only one valid byte sequence for any Unicode character, but some byte sequences are invalid, i.e., they cannot be obtained by encoding any string of Unicode characters into UTF-8.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Some sloppy decoder implementations may accept invalid byte sequences as input and produce a valid Unicode character as output for such a sequence.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] If one uses such a decoder, some Unicode characters effectively have more than one corresponding byte sequence: the valid one and some invalid ones.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] This could lead to security issues similar to the one described in the previous section.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Therefore, if one wants to apply some filter (e.g., a regular expression written in UTF-8) to UTF-8 strings that will later be passed to a decoder that allows invalid byte sequences, one should canonicalize the strings before passing them to the filter.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] In this context, canonicalization is the process of translating every string character to its single valid byte sequence.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] An alternative to canonicalization is to reject any strings containing invalid byte sequences.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] A **canonical URL** is a URL for defining the single source of truth for duplicate content.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] A canonical URL is the URL of the page that Google thinks is most representative from a set of duplicate pages on your site.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] For example, if you have URLs for the same page, such as `https://example.com/?dress=1234` and `https://example.com/dresses/1234`, Google chooses one as canonical.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Note that the pages do not need to be absolutely identical; minor changes in sorting or filtering of list pages do not make the page unique (for example, sorting by price or filtering by item color).
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] The canonical can be in a different domain than a duplicate.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] With the help of canonical URLs, a search engine knows which link should be provided in a query result.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] A canonical link element can get used to define a canonical URL.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] In intranets, manual searching for information is predominant.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] In this case, canonical URLs can be defined in a non-machine-readable form, too.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Canonical URLs are usually the URLs that get used for the share action.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Since the Canonical URL gets used in the search result of search engines, they are in most cases a landing page.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] In web search and search engine optimization (SEO), URL canonicalization deals with web content that has more than one possible URL.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Having multiple URLs for the same web content can cause problems for search engines - specifically in determining which URL should be shown in search results.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Most search engines support the Canonical link element as a hint to which URL should be treated as the true version.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] All of these URLs point to the homepage of Wikipedia, but a search engine will only consider one of them to be the canonical form of the URL.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] A Canonical XML document is by definition an XML document that is in XML Canonical form, defined by The Canonical XML specification.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Briefly, canonicalization removes whitespace within tags, uses particular character encodings, sorts namespace references and eliminates redundant ones, removes XML and DOCTYPE declarations, and transforms relative URIs into absolute URIs.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] The first example contains extra spaces in the closing tag of the first node.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] The second example, which has been canonicalized, has had these spaces removed.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Note that only the spaces within the tags are removed under W3C canonicalization, not those between tags.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] In morphology and lexicography, a lemma is the *canonical form* of a set of words.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] In English, for example, *run*, *runs*, *ran*, and *running* are forms of the same lexeme, so we can select one of them; ex.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Lexical databases such as Unitex use this kind of representation.
[src:path-traversal-defense/canonicalization] Lemmatisation is the process of converting a word to its *canonical form*.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] A **directory traversal**, **path traversal**, or **dot-dot-slash** attack exploits insufficient security validation or sanitization of user-supplied file names, such that characters representing "traverse to parent directory" are passed through to the operating system's file system API.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] An affected application can be exploited to gain unauthorized access to the file system.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] The repeated `../` characters after `/home/users/phpguru/templates/` have caused `include()` to traverse to the root directory, and then include the Unix password file `/etc/passwd`.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Unix `/etc/passwd` is a common file used to demonstrate directory traversal, as it is often used by crackers to try cracking the passwords.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] However, in more recent Unix systems, the `/etc/passwd` file does not contain the hashed passwords, and they are instead located in the `/etc/shadow` file, which cannot be read by unprivileged users on the machine.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Even in that case, though, reading `/etc/passwd` does still show a list of user accounts, which could then become a starting point for further attacks.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Another example is the "Zip Slip" vulnerability that affects several archive file formats like ZIP.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Directory traversal in its simplest form uses the `../` pattern.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Microsoft Windows and DOS directory traversal uses the `..\` or `../` patterns.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Each partition has a separate root directory (labeled `C:\` where C could be any partition), and there is no common root directory above that.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] This means that for most directory vulnerabilities on Windows, attacks are limited to a single partition.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Directory traversal has been the cause of numerous Microsoft vulnerabilities.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Some web applications attempt to prevent directory traversal by scanning the path of a request URI for patterns such as `../`.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] This check is sometimes mistakenly performed before percent-decoding, causing URIs containing patterns like `%2e%2e/` to be accepted despite being decoded into `../` before actual use.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Percent decoding may accidentally be performed multiple times; once before validation, but again afterwards, making the application vulnerable to Double percent-encoding attacks in which illegal characters are replaced by their double-percent-encoded form in order to bypass security countermeasures.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] For example, in a double percent-encoding attack, `../` may be replaced by its double-percent-encoded form `%252E%252E%252F`.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] This kind of vulnerability notably affected versions 5.0 and earlier of Microsoft's IIS web server software.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] A badly implemented UTF-8 decoder may accept characters encoded using more bytes than necessary, leading to overlong encodings, such as `%c0%ae` instead of `%2e` to represent `.`.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] This is specifically forbidden by the UTF-8 standard, but has still led to directory traversal vulnerabilities in software such as the IIS web server.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Some archive formats like zip allow for directory traversal attacks: files in the archive can be written such that they overwrite files on the filesystem by backtracking.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Code that extracts archive files can be written to check that the paths of the files in the archive do not engage in path traversal.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] When a URI request for a file/directory is to be made, build a full path to the file/directory if it exists, and normalize all characters (e.g., `%20` converted to spaces).
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] It is assumed that a 'Document Root' fully qualified, normalized, path is known, and this string has a length *N*.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Assume that no files outside this directory can be served.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Ensure that the first *N* characters of the fully qualified path to the requested file is exactly the same as the 'Document Root'.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] If not, return an error, since the request is clearly out of bounds from what the web-server should be allowed to serve.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] Using a hard-coded predefined file extension to suffix the path does not necessarily limit the scope of the attack to files of that file extension.
[src:path-traversal-defense/directory-traversal-attack] The user can use the NULL character (indicating the end of the string) in order to bypass everything after the `$_GET`.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] File upload is becoming a more and more essential part of any application, where the user is able to upload their photo, their CV, or a video showcasing a project they are working on.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] The application should be able to fend off bogus and malicious files in a way to keep the application and the users safe.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] In order to assess and know exactly what controls to implement, knowing what you're facing is essential to protect your assets.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] The following sections will hopefully showcase the risks accompanying the file upload functionality.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Client-side active content (XSS, CSRF, etc.) that could endanger other users if the files are publicly retrievable.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Initiate a DoS attack by requesting lots of files.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] File content that could be deemed as illegal, offensive, or dangerous (*e.g.* personal data, copyrighted data, etc.) which will make you a host for such malicious files.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] There is no silver bullet in validating user content.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Implementing a defense in depth approach is key to make the upload process harder and more locked down to the needs and requirements for the service.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Implementing multiple techniques is key and recommended, as no one technique is enough to secure the service.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Refer to the Input Validation CS to properly parse and process the extension.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Ensure the usage of *business-critical* extensions only, without allowing any type of *non-required* extensions.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Based on the needs of the application, ensure the **least harmful** and the **lowest risk** file types to be used.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Identify potentially harmful file types and block extensions that you regard harmful to your service.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Please be aware that blocking specific extensions is a weak protection method on its own.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] The Unrestricted File Upload vulnerability article describes how attackers may attempt to bypass such a check.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Other than defining the extension of the uploaded file, its MIME-type can be checked for a quick protection against simple file upload attacks.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] This can be done preferably in an allowlist approach; otherwise, this can be done in a denylist approach.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] In conjunction with content-type validation, validating the file's signature can be checked and verified against the expected file that should be received.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Filenames can endanger the system in multiple ways, either by using non acceptable characters, or by using special and restricted filenames.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] For Windows, refer to the following MSDN guide.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] For a wider overview on different filesystems and how they treat files, refer to Wikipedia's Filename page.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] In order to avoid the above mentioned threat, creating a **random string** as a filename, such as generating a UUID/GUID, is essential.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] If the filename is required by the business needs, proper input validation should be done for client-side (*e.g.* active content that results in XSS and CSRF attacks) and back-end side (*e.g.* special files overwrite or creation) attack vectors.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Filename length limits should be taken into consideration based on the system storing the files, as each system has its own filename length limit.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] As mentioned in the Public File Retrieval section, file content can contain malicious, inappropriate, or illegal data.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] The File Upload service should allow users to report illegal content, and copyright owners to report abuse.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] If there are enough resources, manual file review should be conducted in a sandboxed environment before releasing the files to the public.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Adding some automation to the review could be helpful, which is a harsh process and should be well studied before its usage.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Some services (*e.g.* Virus Total) provide APIs to scan files against well known malicious file hashes.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Some frameworks can check and validate the raw content type and validating it against predefined file types, such as in ASP.NET Drawing Library.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Beware of data leakage threats and information gathering by public services.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] The location where the files should be stored must be chosen based on security and business requirements.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Store the files **outside the webroot**, where only administrative access is allowed.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Storing files in a studied manner in databases is one additional technique.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] This is sometimes used for automatic backup processes, non file-system attacks, and permissions issues.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] In return, this opens up the door to performance issues (in some cases), storage considerations for the database and its backups, and this opens up the door to SQLi attack.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] This is advised only when a DBA is on the team and that this process shows to be an improvement on storing them on the file-system.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] The application should set proper size limits for the upload service in order to protect the file storage capacity.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] If the system is going to extract the files or process them, the file size limit should be considered after file decompression is conducted and by using secure methods to calculate zip files size.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] For more on this, see how to Safely extract files from ZipInputStream, Java's input stream to handle ZIP files.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] The application should set proper request limits as well for the download service if available to protect the server from DoS attacks.
[src:path-traversal-defense/file-upload-cheat-sheet] Document Upload Protection repository written by Dominique for certain document types in Java.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] A **path** (or **filepath**, **file path**, **pathname**, or similar) is a string that uniquely identifies an item in a hierarchical file system.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Generally, a path is composed of directory names, special format specifiers, and optionally a filename, all separated by delimiters.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] This delimiter can vary by operating system, but popular, modern systems use the slash `/`, backslash `\`, or colon `:`.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] The case-sensitivity of individual path components will vary based on operating system, or based on options specified at the time of a file system's creation or first use.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] A path can be either **relative** or **absolute**.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] A relative path is a path in relation to another, most often the working directory.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] An absolute path indicates a location regardless of the current directory; that is, it specifies all path components starting from the file system's root, and does not depend on context like a relative path does.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Paths are also essential for locating hierarchically-organized network resources, as seen in URLs and UNC paths.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Multics first introduced a hierarchical file system with directories (separated by ">") in the mid-1960s.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Around 1970, Unix introduced the slash `/` as its directory separator.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Originally, MS-DOS did not support directories.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] When adding the feature, using the Unix standard of a slash was not a good option since many existing commands used a slash as the switch prefix (i.e., `dir /w`).
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] In contrast, Unix uses the dash `-` as the switch prefix.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] The backslash `\` was ultimately chosen instead for its similarity to the slash and not conflicting with existing commands.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] However, some areas of Windows do accept or understand Unix-style slashes also, such as PowerShell.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Most programming languages use the path representation of the underlying system, but some may also be system-independent.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Most Unix-like systems use a similar syntax.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] POSIX allows treating a path beginning with two slashes in an implementation-defined manner, though in other cases systems must treat consecutive slashes as one.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Many applications on Unix-like systems (for example, scp, rcp, and rsync) use resource definitions such as `hostname:/directorypath/resource`, or URI schemes with the service name (here 'smb'), like `smb://hostname/directorypath/resource`.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] When macOS was being developed, it inherited some pathname choices from Classic Mac OS and the Unix-like NeXTSTEP.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] The classic Mac OS uses a `:` while Unix and Unix-like systems use a `/` as the path delimiter.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] DOS and Windows have no single root directory; a root exists for each storage drive, indicated with a drive letter or through UNC.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Directory and file name comparisons are case-insensitive: "test.TXT" would match "Test.txt".
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] In the Windows API, file I/O functions automatically convert `/` into `\` (except when using the `\\?\` prefix).
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Paths using standard Windows APIs (dating back to DOS and Win9x), were limited to 260 characters, or less, as defined by the environment variable *MAX_PATH*.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] For backwards compatibility with legacy applications this limitation was not removed until Windows 10, build 1607, when it could be expanded to 32,767.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Windows NT always supported the 32,767 path length internally but only if using Unicode APIs or forcing UNC paths by the `\\?\` prefix.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Japanese and Korean versions of Windows often displayed the '¥' character or the '₩' character instead of the directory separator.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] This is because, while in ANSI codepages the character at 0x5C was the backslash, in Japanese and Korean codepages 0x5C was the yen and won signs, respectively.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Therefore, when the character for a backslash was used, other glyphs appeared.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] The Microsoft **Universal Naming Convention** (**UNC**, **uniform naming convention**, or **network path**), is a syntax to describe the location of a network resource, such as a shared file, directory, or printer.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Some Windows interfaces allow or require UNC syntax for WebDAV share access, rather than a URL.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] The UNC syntax is extended with optional components to denote use of SSL and TCP/IP port number.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Thus, the WebDAV URL of `https://hostname:443/SharedFolder/Resource` becomes `\\hostname@SSL@443\SharedFolder\Resource`.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] When viewed remotely, the "SharedFolder" may have a name different from what a program on the server sees when opening "\SharedFolder".
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Instead, the SharedFolder name consists of an arbitrary name assigned during creation of the share.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] Since UNCs start with two backslashes, and the backslash is also used for escape sequences and in regular expressions, cases of leaning toothpick syndrome may arise.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] An escaped string for a regular expression matching a UNC begins with 8 backslashes `\\\\\\\\` because the string and regular expression both require escaping.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-computing] This can be simplified by using raw strings, such as `@"\\\\"` in C#, `r'\\\\'` in Python, or `qr{\\\\}` in Perl.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] A path traversal attack (also known as directory traversal) aims to access files and directories that are stored outside the web root folder.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] By manipulating variables that reference files with “dot-dot-slash (../)” sequences and its variations or by using absolute file paths, it may be possible to access arbitrary files and directories stored on file system including application source code or configuration and critical system files.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] It should be noted that access to files is limited by system operational access control (such as in the case of locked or in-use files on the Microsoft Windows operating system).
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] This attack is also known as “dot-dot-slash”, “directory traversal”, “directory climbing” and “backtracking”.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] All but the most simple web applications have to include local resources, such as images, themes, other scripts, and so on.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] Every time a resource or file is included by the application, there is a risk that an attacker may be able to include a file or remote resource you didn’t authorize.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] See the OWASP Testing Guide article on how to test for path traversal vulnerabilities.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] Note that web containers perform one level of decoding on percent encoded values from forms and URLs.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] In many operating systems, null bytes `%00` can be injected to terminate the filename.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] will result in the Java application seeing a string that ends with “.pdf” and the operating system will see a file that ends in “.doc”.
[src:path-traversal-defense/path-traversal] Attackers may use this trick to bypass validation routines.
